{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_0","type":"agent_message","text":"final_filename: p25.cir\n\nObjective:\nDesign a single-supply inverting op amp differentiator using input node Vin and output node Vout. Vin must be driven by an explicit triangle-wave independent voltage source. The transient output at Vout should approximate the differentiated form of the triangle input: a square-like waveform with polarity inversion.\n\nTopology:\nUse an inverting op amp differentiator:\n- Capacitor C1 connects from Vin to the op amp inverting input node.\n- Resistor Rf connects from Vout back to the op amp inverting input node.\n- The op amp non-inverting input is biased at a mid-supply reference Vref = 2.5 V so the differentiator can operate from a single 5 V supply.\n- The inverting input acts as a virtual Vref node during linear operation.\n- The output Vout should swing around Vref, positive when Vin has negative slope and negative when Vin has positive slope, limited by the 0 V to 5 V supply rails.\n\nRequired devices:\n- VDD independent DC source from VDD to 0, value 5 V.\n- Vin independent triangle-wave voltage source connected from Vin to 0.\n- Vref generation, preferably a resistor divider from VDD to 0 with equal resistors, producing 2.5 V at node Vref.\n- Op amp macromodel or behavioral voltage-controlled source powered from VDD and 0, with high open-loop gain and output limiting between 0 V and 5 V.\n- C1 from Vin to the inverting input node, for example node NINV.\n- Rf from Vout to NINV.\n- Optional large resistor from NINV to Vref only if needed for DC convergence, but it must be much larger than Rf so it does not dominate differentiator behavior.\n\nBiasing assumptions:\n- Use VDD = 5 V.\n- Use Vref = 2.5 V as the single-supply signal reference.\n- Vin triangle wave should be centered around Vref, not ground, so the op amp input common-mode range is reasonable.\n- Choose triangle amplitude small enough that differentiated output does not hard-saturate unless clipping is intentionally visible.\n- Nominal example values: C1 = 10 nF, Rf = 10 kOhm. The ideal differentiated output follows:\n  Vout ≈ Vref - Rf*C1*dVin/dt\n- If using a behavioral op amp, limit Vout between 0 V and 5 V.\n\nAnalysis:\nInclude:\n.tran 1u 10m\n\nOutput constraints:\n- Nodes Vin and Vout must both appear explicitly in the final netlist.\n- Vin must be driven by a triangle-wave independent voltage source.\n- Vout must be the op amp output node.\n- The transient waveform at Vin should be triangular.\n- The transient waveform at Vout should be square-like, centered around Vref, with inverted differentiator polarity:\n  rising Vin ramp produces lower Vout level;\n  falling Vin ramp produces higher Vout level."}}
